english:
  title: Record of the Hall for Cultivating Vastness
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: 'The vastness of spirit—how difficult it is to speak of such a thing. Only water can give it form and expression. We humans receive the vital essence of the five elements at birth, and thus by observing the vastness of water, we come to know the vastness within ourselves. The vastness of water swallows heaven and earth, cradles sun and moon, holds within it the transformations of the great fish and the great bird, yet its source flows from but a single drop. The vastness of spirit reaches to the extreme of vastness and strength, filling all of heaven and earth, nurturing all things within itself, and yet when gathered inward, it does not overflow the space of one''s own heart. Water holds its place among the five elements, receiving the generative numbers of heaven and earth. We humans, as the most refined of all things, first inherit the creative heart of heaven and earth. Both we and water are living things, both partake of the same vastness—such is the kinship of their essence. Vastness, then, is the appearance of great abundance flowing forth. The spirit is the true vital breath of heaven and earth, fullness dwelling within our own form. When one nourishes the source within and applies the work of reflective knowing, righteous principle naturally arises, just as water continually flows. But should one be obscured by selfish desires, one shrinks and withers, knowing oneself to be small. The essential way to cultivate this vastness lies in righteousness without harm. To seek openness through contrary means is like blocking the source and damming the flow while hoping for water''s vastness. Mencius was skilled in cultivating this vital essence, thus he said: "One who has gazed upon the sea finds it hard to call other waters great." This shows that what we perceive suffices to nourish what we cultivate, and reveals that the source flows forth from heaven itself. The truly skilled cultivator of spirit, through inner reflection free from shame, needs not wait for water''s vastness—their own spirit is already vastly flowing. When I journeyed southward, each day I would climb the hills to gaze upon the sea, seeking to ease my heart''s yearning for the distant capital. Near the shore stood a small hall. Upon inquiry, I learned it was the retreat of a reclusive gentleman named Lee. As I observed the vastness of water, contemplation of spirit''s cultivation took hold of me. Thus I named it the Hall for Cultivating Vastness and wrote this record, honoring Lee''s request. Standing in his hall, watching the tides ebb and flow, one perceives the beginningless nature of yin and yang. Observing how water fills its channel before proceeding, one grasps that learning admits no shortcuts. Thus here we find not merely the cultivation of spirit, but profound lessons in method and meaning. The will is the commander, the vital essence is the soldier. With a worthy general, orders are executed; without one, commands fall silent. The noble person must use will to command spirit. To observe water and understand the way of cultivating spirit, to cultivate spirit and grasp the essence of cultivating will—in this hall, I shall surely find my truth.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "vastness of spirit" (浩然之氣) refers to Mencius's concept of cultivating an all-pervading moral and vital force through virtue and righteousness.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusion to "the great fish and the great bird" (鯤鵬) references Zhuangzi's famous parable of transformation and boundlessness.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mencius''s saying about viewing the sea appears in his Works (孟子): ''One who has observed the sea will find it hard to regard other waters as worthy of mention.'''
  - key: ''
    value: The metaphor of 'will as commander and spirit as soldier' reflects Neo-Confucian thought on the relationship between moral intention and vital essence.
